Could somebody please explain why is it not possible to use a stack for this question? Solved as follows:

Basically I'm sorting by first element asc and by second - desc; 
Then I store reference of how many element on the left is current elemen contained by (incrementing previous index by 1)
If new element is not contained in previous one - I pop elements from stack until find any element that contains current one and increment the index accordingly;

Could not think of any edge cases when this would not work. Can you please explain what I'm missing?  

public static List<int[]> solve(int[][] intervals) {
        Arrays.sort(intervals, Comparator.comparingInt((int[] a) -> a[0])
                .thenComparing(Comparator.comparingInt((int[] a) -> a[1]).reversed())); 
        int maxContainedBy = 0;
        List<int[]> result = new ArrayList<>();
        Deque<int[]> deque = new LinkedList<>();
        for (int[] i : intervals) {
            int[] prev = deque.peek();

            while (prev != null && i[0] > prev[0]) {
                deque.pop();
                prev = deque.peek();
            }

            if (prev == null) {
                deque.push(new int[]{i[1], 0});
                continue;
            }

            int containedBy = prev[1] + 1;
            if (containedBy > maxContainedBy) {
                maxContainedBy = containedBy;
                result.clear();
            }
            if (containedBy == maxContainedBy) {
                result.add(i);
            }
            deque.push(new int[]{i[1], containedBy});
        }
        return result;
    }

